Yes — in that revision it’s a bug in `@apply`, not a misunderstanding.

`border-dotted` is generated twice:

```css
.border-dotted { border-width: 0; } /* reset */
.border-dotted { border-style: dotted; }
```

With classes, the generated stylesheet’s overall order lets `.border` set a width between those two rules. But `@apply border-dotted` copies both matching rules directly into your selector, resulting in:

```css
.foo {
  border-width: 0;
  border-style: dotted;
}
```

So the dotted border has no visible width.

A short-term workaround is to set a width after applying it:

```css
.foo {
  @apply border-dotted;
  border-width: 1px;
}
```

Applying `border` after it would reset the style back to `solid`, so that isn’t a reliable workaround.
